// CH 2 — NATIONALISM IN INDIA
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

const ch2_pyqs = [
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"What was the Non-Cooperation Movement? Why was it launched and what were its main features?", answer:"The Non-Cooperation Movement (1920-22) was launched by Mahatma Gandhi in alliance with the Khilafat Movement. Reasons: (1) Khilafat issue — the Ottoman Caliph (head of Islam) was being dismantled by the British. (2) Jallianwala Bagh massacre (1919) and the Rowlatt Act. (3) The unjust peace settlement after WWI. Features: (1) Surrendering titles and honours. (2) Boycott of civil services, army, police, courts, legislatures, schools. (3) Boycott of foreign goods and burning of foreign cloth. (4) Picketing of liquor shops. Gandhi believed if all Indians cooperated, British rule would collapse within a year. The movement was called off in 1922 after the Chauri Chaura violence where a mob burned a police station.", year:2023, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"Explain the concept of Satyagraha as developed by Gandhi. How was it different from passive resistance?", answer:"Satyagraha means 'truth-force' or 'soul-force'. Gandhi believed that if the cause is just and the fighter follows truth and non-violence, moral force would ultimately prevail over physical force. Key features: (1) Non-violence (ahimsa) was central — the oppressor's conscience must be awakened. (2) The Satyagrahi must be willing to suffer, not inflict suffering. (3) No hatred toward the oppressor — only rejection of the wrong. Difference from passive resistance: Passive resistance is a weapon of the weak — reluctant, negative. Satyagraha is a weapon of the strong — positive, assertive, requiring immense courage and self-discipline. Gandhi first used Satyagraha in South Africa (1893-1914), then in Champaran (1917), Kheda (1918), Ahmedabad (1918), and nationally in 1920.", year:2023, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"What was the Rowlatt Act? How did Indians react to it?", answer:"The Rowlatt Act (1919) was passed by the Imperial Legislative Council despite being opposed by all Indian members. It gave the British government the authority to: (1) Arrest and imprison suspected revolutionaries without trial. (2) Try political cases without a jury. (3) Detain people without bail. Indian reaction: (1) Nationwide protests and hartals (shutdowns). (2) Gandhi called for a national campaign against it. (3) The protests culminated in the Jallianwala Bagh massacre (April 13, 1919) when General Dyer ordered firing on a peaceful crowd — killing hundreds. (4) The massacre shattered Indian trust in British rule and accelerated the nationalist movement significantly.", year:2022, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"What was the significance of the Salt March (Dandi March) of 1930?", answer:"The Salt March (March 12 - April 5, 1930): Gandhi walked 240 miles from Sabarmati Ashram to Dandi to break the salt law. Significance: (1) Salt was chosen because every Indian used it — rich, poor, Hindu, Muslim. Breaking the salt monopoly was a symbolic act of defiance everyone could relate to. (2) It launched the Civil Disobedience Movement. (3) It attracted worldwide media attention. (4) It demonstrated that ordinary Indians — including women — could defy British authority. (5) It was followed by boycotts, picketing, forest law violations. The British responded with arrests and beatings, which further radicalised Indian opinion. The movement forced the British to negotiate — leading to the Gandhi-Irwin Pact (1931).", year:2022, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"What were the limitations of the Civil Disobedience Movement? Why did it not fully achieve its goals?", answer:"Limitations: (1) Muslim political organisations did not fully participate after the breakdown of Hindu-Muslim unity following the Khilafat collapse. (2) The business class was divided — initially supported but withdrew when the movement became too radical. (3) Dalits and depressed classes were not fully integrated — Dr. Ambedkar opposed Gandhi's approach to caste. (4) The British used repression effectively — arrested thousands including Gandhi. (5) The Gandhi-Irwin Pact (1931) suspended the movement but achieved only minor concessions. (6) When Gandhi attended the Round Table Conference in London, he found the British unwilling to grant full independence. Despite limitations, it mobilised millions and demonstrated the power of mass nationalism.", year:2021, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"How did Gandhi try to incorporate the peasants and workers into the nationalist movement?", answer:"Gandhi's methods of incorporating lower classes: (1) Champaran Satyagraha (1917) — supported indigo peasants against forced cultivation. (2) Kheda Satyagraha (1918) — supported peasants demanding tax relief after crop failure. (3) Ahmedabad Mill Strike (1918) — sided with textile workers against mill owners. (4) He wore simple clothes (dhoti, loincloth) to identify with the poor. (5) He adopted spinning the charkha (spinning wheel) as a symbol — cotton symbolised economic self-reliance. (6) He championed abolition of untouchability — calling Dalits 'Harijans'. However, Gandhi stopped short of challenging the class structure or zamindari system — he wanted class harmony, not class conflict.", year:2021, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"What was the Khilafat Movement? How did it contribute to Hindu-Muslim unity in the Non-Cooperation Movement?", answer:"The Khilafat Movement (1919-24) was launched by Muhammad Ali and Shaukat Ali (the Ali Brothers) to protect the Ottoman Caliph — head of the Islamic world — who was being dismantled by the victorious Allied Powers after WWI. Hindu-Muslim unity: (1) Gandhi saw it as an opportunity to unite Hindus and Muslims in one national movement. (2) Gandhi supported the Khilafat cause; Muslim leaders supported Gandhi's Non-Cooperation Movement. (3) This produced an unprecedented Hindu-Muslim alliance — the high point being 1920-22. (4) The alliance began collapsing after 1922 when the movement was suspended and after Kemal Ataturk abolished the Caliphate himself in 1924, removing the Khilafat issue.", year:2020, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"Why did Gandhi call off the Non-Cooperation Movement in 1922?", answer:"Gandhi called off the Non-Cooperation Movement in February 1922 after the Chauri Chaura incident in which a mob of protesters attacked and set fire to a police station in Gorakhpur, killing 22 policemen. Gandhi's reasoning: (1) The movement had turned violent — contradicting the fundamental principle of Satyagraha (non-violence). (2) If violence spread, the British would use it to justify brutal repression. (3) Gandhi believed the nation was not yet ready for full non-violent discipline. (4) He wanted to preserve the moral high ground that non-violence provided. Many nationalist leaders, including Jawaharlal Nehru and Subhas Chandra Bose, were deeply disappointed by this decision, arguing that momentum had been sacrificed.", year:2020, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"What was the significance of the Jallianwala Bagh massacre for Indian nationalism?", answer:"The Jallianwala Bagh massacre (April 13, 1919) occurred when General Dyer ordered his troops to fire on a peaceful crowd gathered for the Baisakhi festival — killing an estimated 400+ people and wounding thousands. Significance: (1) It shattered the belief that British rule was benevolent. (2) It radicalised Indian public opinion — even moderate nationalists now questioned cooperation with Britain. (3) Tagore returned his knighthood in protest. (4) The Hunter Commission (inquiry) justified Dyer's action — deepening Indian outrage. (5) It directly contributed to Gandhi launching the Non-Cooperation Movement in 1920. (6) It became a defining moment in Indian collective memory — a symbol of colonial brutality.", year:2019, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"What were the problems with unifying different groups under one nationalist movement in India?", answer:"Multiple divisions challenged unified Indian nationalism: (1) Religious divisions — Hindu-Muslim tensions, especially over cow protection, music before mosques, separate electorates. (2) Caste divisions — upper-caste dominance of nationalist movement alienated Dalits and lower castes. Dr. Ambedkar and Gandhi clashed over the Poona Pact (1932). (3) Class divisions — landlords/industrialists had different interests from peasants and workers. (4) Regional identities — different languages, cultures, histories. (5) Gender — women participated but were expected to return to traditional roles after independence. (6) Tribal communities had their own grievances about land and forests. Gandhi tried to create a broad coalition but these tensions never fully resolved.", year:2019, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"What symbols did the Indian National Congress use to create a sense of national unity?", answer:"The Congress used several symbols: (1) The national flag — originally with spinning wheel (charkha), later the Ashoka Chakra. (2) Gandhi's spinning wheel (charkha) — symbolising self-reliance, cottage industry, and opposition to foreign cloth. (3) The bonfire of foreign clothes — public burning of imported British cloth. (4) Vande Mataram — the national song from Bankimchandra's novel Anandamath, though it was later controversial for Muslims. (5) Bharat Mata (Mother India) imagery — personification of the nation as a mother goddess, uniting emotional and religious sentiment. (6) Swadeshi products — using Indian-made goods as an act of patriotism. These symbols worked across language and class barriers to create emotional belonging.", year:2023, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"How did the plantation workers of Assam participate in the nationalist movement?", answer:"Plantation workers (tea estate labourers) in Assam had special grievances: (1) Under the Inland Migration Act, they were not free to leave plantations without employers' permission. (2) When they heard of Gandhi's movements and the promise of swaraj (self-rule), they believed they would be free. (3) Thousands of workers left plantations and tried to return to their villages — but were stranded when a railway strike stopped trains. (4) They were caught and beaten by the police. Their participation showed how nationalism spread even to the most isolated and exploited communities. But their specific demands (freedom from plantation bondage) were not fully addressed by the mainstream Congress movement.", year:2022, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"What is the significance of Alluri Sitaram Raju in the context of tribal participation in nationalism?", answer:"Alluri Sitaram Raju (1897-1924) was the leader of the Rampa Rebellion (1922-24) in the Andhra Pradesh tribal region. Significance: (1) He claimed to be inspired by Gandhi's Non-Cooperation Movement. (2) He talked about the superiority of Indian traditions over Western ways. (3) He led tribal people (Gonds and Koyas) in raids on police stations and armouries. (4) He was captured and shot by the British in 1924. (5) His rebellion showed how nationalist ideas mixed with tribal grievances (about forest laws, land rights) to create resistance. He represented how ordinary and marginalised people interpreted nationalism in their own terms — not always in the Congress's non-violent terms.", year:2021, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"How did the Congress try to solve the problem of different languages in creating Indian nationalism?", answer:"The language problem was significant — India had hundreds of languages. Congress solutions: (1) Reorganisation of provinces on linguistic lines was accepted in principle. (2) Hindi was promoted as the national language — though this alienated non-Hindi speakers in south and eastern India. (3) Gandhi himself used Hindustani (a blend of Hindi and Urdu) as a link language. (4) Vernacular literature was used for nationalist propaganda. (5) The Congress held sessions in different regional languages. (6) The principle of 'unity in diversity' accepted linguistic diversity as strength. However, the language issue remained contentious and continued after independence, with demands for linguistic states.", year:2020, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"Compare Gandhi's vision of Swaraj with that of the radical nationalists.", answer:"Gandhi's vision of Swaraj: (1) Self-rule through non-violent mass movement. (2) Village-based economy — cottage industries, spinning, simple living. (3) Class harmony — no class conflict. (4) Moral regeneration — truth, non-violence, self-sacrifice. (5) Cooperation between communities. Radical nationalists' vision (Bose, Bhagat Singh): (1) Violent revolution if necessary. (2) Complete independence (Purna Swaraj) without compromise. (3) Socialist economic transformation — end of capitalist exploitation. (4) Faster, more confrontational methods. (5) Sceptical of Gandhi's willingness to compromise with British. The key difference: Gandhi saw Swaraj as a moral-spiritual transformation; radicals saw it primarily as political-economic liberation.", year:2019, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
];

const ch2_easyMCQ = [
  { q:"The Non-Cooperation Movement was launched by Gandhi in:", opts:["1915","1919","1920","1922"], ans:2, exp:"Gandhi launched the Non-Cooperation Movement in 1920, in alliance with the Khilafat Movement. It was the first mass national movement under Gandhi's leadership, asking Indians to boycott British institutions, goods and services." },
  { q:"What does 'Satyagraha' literally mean?", opts:["Non-violence","Truth-force or soul-force","Civil disobedience","Boycott"], ans:1, exp:"Satyagraha comes from Sanskrit: 'Satya' (truth) + 'Agraha' (firmness/force). It means truth-force or soul-force — the idea that adherence to truth and moral force is more powerful than physical violence." },
  { q:"The Rowlatt Act was passed in which year?", opts:["1915","1917","1919","1921"], ans:2, exp:"The Rowlatt Act was passed in 1919 by the Imperial Legislative Council over the unanimous opposition of all Indian members. It allowed arrest and imprisonment without trial." },
  { q:"What event is associated with Jallianwala Bagh?", opts:["Beginning of Civil Disobedience","Firing on a peaceful crowd by General Dyer","Gandhi's arrest","The Salt March"], ans:1, exp:"On April 13, 1919 (Baisakhi day), General Reginald Dyer ordered his troops to fire on a large unarmed crowd gathered at Jallianwala Bagh in Amritsar, killing hundreds and wounding thousands." },
  { q:"The Salt March began from:", opts:["Delhi","Bardoli","Sabarmati Ashram","Dandi"], ans:2, exp:"Gandhi began the Dandi March from Sabarmati Ashram, Ahmedabad on March 12, 1930. He walked 240 miles to Dandi on the Gujarat coast, where he made salt by evaporating seawater, breaking the British salt monopoly." },
  { q:"The Civil Disobedience Movement was launched after the:", opts:["Rowlatt Act","Simon Commission Report","Salt March","Jallianwala Bagh massacre"], ans:2, exp:"The Civil Disobedience Movement was formally launched after Gandhi's Salt March and salt-making at Dandi (April 6, 1930). The act of making salt — breaking British law — was the symbolic opening of the movement." },
  { q:"Who led the Khilafat Movement in India?", opts:["Gandhi and Nehru","Mohammad Ali and Shaukat Ali","Iqbal and Jinnah","Ambedkar and Gandhi"], ans:1, exp:"The Khilafat Movement was led by the Ali Brothers — Muhammad Ali and Shaukat Ali. They wanted to protect the Ottoman Caliph (head of the Islamic world) from being dismantled by the British after WWI." },
  { q:"The Chauri Chaura incident that led Gandhi to call off the Non-Cooperation Movement happened in:", opts:["1920","1921","1922","1924"], ans:2, exp:"In February 1922 at Chauri Chaura in Gorakhpur (UP), a mob of protesters attacked and set fire to a police station, killing 22 policemen. Gandhi called off the Non-Cooperation Movement because of this violence." },
  { q:"Which act gave the British power to arrest Indians without trial?", opts:["Indian Councils Act","Rowlatt Act","Vernacular Press Act","Ilbert Bill"], ans:1, exp:"The Rowlatt Act (1919) gave British authorities the power to arrest, imprison and try people suspected of terrorism without a jury and without bail — essentially a 'no appeal, no vakil, no daleel' law." },
  { q:"Gandhi's first Satyagraha in India was at:", opts:["Dandi","Bardoli","Champaran","Kheda"], ans:2, exp:"Gandhi's first Satyagraha in India was at Champaran in Bihar (1917), where he supported indigo farmers (nil farmers) against the tinkathia system that forced them to grow indigo on 3/20ths of their land for the British planters." },
  { q:"Vande Mataram was written by:", opts:["Rabindranath Tagore","Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay","Subramania Bharati","Maithili Sharan Gupt"], ans:1, exp:"Vande Mataram was written by Bankim Chandra Chattopadhyay and appeared in his 1882 novel Anandamath. It became one of the most powerful nationalist songs, though it was later controversial for religious reasons." },
  { q:"Bharat Mata was first visualised as a goddess by:", opts:["Gandhi","Tagore","Abanindranath Tagore","Bal Gangadhar Tilak"], ans:2, exp:"Bharat Mata (Mother India) was first visualised as a woman in a painting by Abanindranath Tagore (nephew of Rabindranath Tagore). She was depicted as an ascetic figure holding books, paddy, a white cloth and garland." },
  { q:"What is 'swaraj'?", opts:["Foreign rule","Self-rule or independence","Economic development","Non-violence"], ans:1, exp:"Swaraj literally means 'self-rule' (swa=self, raj=rule). In the nationalist context, it meant Indian self-governance and independence from British colonial rule. Gandhi used the term to encompass both political independence and moral self-discipline." },
  { q:"The Indian National Congress declared Purna Swaraj (complete independence) at:", opts:["The Lahore Session 1929","The Calcutta Session 1928","The Nagpur Session 1920","The Bombay Session 1915"], ans:0, exp:"At the Lahore Session of the Indian National Congress (December 1929), presided over by Jawaharlal Nehru, the Congress passed the Purna Swaraj resolution demanding complete independence from British rule. January 26, 1930 was declared Independence Day." },
  { q:"Who said 'Swaraj is my birthright and I will have it'?", opts:["Gandhi","Gokhale","Tilak","Nehru"], ans:2, exp:"Bal Gangadhar Tilak famously declared 'Swaraj is my birthright and I will have it!' This assertive nationalism contrasted with the 'moderate' Congress leaders who sought constitutional reforms within the British system." },
];

const ch2_mediumMCQ = [
  { q:"Why was salt chosen as the symbol for the Civil Disobedience Movement?", opts:["Salt was expensive and only the rich could afford it","Every Indian — rich or poor, Hindu or Muslim — used salt, making it a unifying symbol of colonial injustice and a law every Indian could break","Salt was a religious symbol","Salt was the main Indian export"], ans:1, exp:"The genius of choosing salt was its universality. Every Indian used salt; the British monopoly on salt and the salt tax affected everyone regardless of religion, caste or class. By breaking the salt law, any Indian could participate in civil disobedience. Gandhi also knew the visual drama of making salt from seawater would attract worldwide media attention." },
  { q:"Why did the business community initially support but later withdraw from the Civil Disobedience Movement?", opts:["They were paid by the British to stop","They feared the movement was becoming too radical — threatening their own economic interests as it moved toward challenging property and class structures","They were busy with trade","Business people were not nationalists"], ans:1, exp:"Indian industrialists (like the Tatas and Birlas) initially supported the movement because it threatened British competition. But when the movement began encouraging radical peasant and worker demands (land reform, higher wages), the business class feared social instability. They preferred nationalism that brought them power over British competitors without challenging the capitalist order." },
  { q:"How did women participate in the Civil Disobedience Movement?", opts:["They stayed home and supported from there","They took leading roles — picketing liquor shops, burning foreign cloth, refusing to buy foreign goods, marching in protests despite police brutality","They only wrote letters of support","Women were excluded by Gandhi"], ans:1, exp:"Women's participation in the Civil Disobedience Movement was unprecedented. Thousands picketed liquor and foreign cloth shops, marched despite arrests and police lathi charges, and ran homes while men were in prison. Gandhi himself encouraged women's participation, seeing it as both strategically valuable and personally liberating for women. This transformed Indian women's public role." },
  { q:"Why did Dalits have ambiguous feelings about the nationalist movement?", opts:["They did not want independence","They faced discrimination not just from British but from upper-caste Hindus within the nationalist movement — their specific demands for separate electorates and social equality were often not prioritised","Dalits were not Indian","They supported British rule"], ans:1, exp:"Dr. B.R. Ambedkar articulated this tension: for Dalits, independence from Britain meant trading one master (the British) for another (upper-caste Hindus) unless caste discrimination was abolished. The Poona Pact (1932) controversy — where Gandhi fasted against separate electorates for Dalits — showed this tension. Ambedkar ultimately accepted reserved seats within the general electorate, but the tension between nationalism and caste justice was never fully resolved." },
  { q:"How did the Simon Commission contribute to radicalising Indian nationalism?", opts:["It gave Indians representation","It recommended independence","The Commission had no Indian member — an all-white British body deciding India's future — provoking nationwide protests under the slogan 'Simon Go Back'","It was welcomed by all Indians"], ans:2, exp:"The Simon Commission (1927) was appointed to review the Government of India Act but had no Indian members. This was seen as an insult — Indians were not trusted to determine their own political future. Nationwide protests followed, including the Lahore protest where Lala Lajpat Rai was injured in a police lathi charge and later died. This death radicalised youth — Bhagat Singh and others killed the police officer responsible." },
  { q:"Why did Gandhi suspend the Non-Cooperation Movement in 1922 despite criticism from other leaders?", opts:["He was tired","The British threatened him","The Chauri Chaura violence violated his core principle of non-violence — he believed a movement built on violence would ultimately fail morally even if it succeeded politically","He made a deal with the British"], ans:2, exp:"Gandhi's decision revealed the ideological heart of Satyagraha: non-violence was not tactical but fundamental. A movement that used violence to achieve independence would, Gandhi believed, produce a violent independent India. Leaders like Nehru and Bose disagreed — they saw it as sacrificing political opportunity for moral purity. This debate about means and ends runs throughout nationalist history." },
  { q:"How did the experience of WWI contribute to Indian nationalism?", opts:["Indians were not affected by WWI","WWI had no economic impact on India","WWI caused inflation, food shortages, forced recruitment and taxation in India — creating widespread resentment that Gandhi mobilised into mass nationalism from 1917 onwards","WWI made Indians loyal to Britain"], ans:2, exp:"WWI's impact on India was devastating: (1) Forced recruitment — thousands of Indian soldiers died in European and other fronts. (2) Inflation — prices doubled while wages stagnated. (3) Custom duties and income tax raised. (4) Famines in 1918-19. Indians had expected political rewards for their wartime loyalty — instead they got the Rowlatt Act (1919). This betrayal radicalised Indian opinion." },
  { q:"What was the significance of the Lahore Session of Congress (1929) for Indian nationalism?", opts:["Gandhi became president","The Congress was founded","The Congress declared Purna Swaraj (complete independence) under Nehru's presidency, moving beyond dominion status to full independence as the goal","The Congress split into two groups"], ans:2, exp:"The Lahore Session (1929) was a turning point: (1) Jawaharlal Nehru became president — symbolising youth leadership. (2) Purna Swaraj (complete independence) replaced 'dominion status' as the goal. (3) January 26, 1930 declared as Independence Day — people across India took the pledge. This prepared the ground for the Civil Disobedience Movement (1930) and the eventual demand for partition of British India." },
  { q:"How did tribal communities interpret the nationalist movement differently from urban middle-class nationalists?", opts:["They did not participate","They wanted to remain under British rule","Tribal communities merged nationalist slogans with their specific grievances about land, forests and autonomy — Alluri Sitaram Raju in Andhra combined Gandhian ideas with tribal resistance to forest laws","Tribal people understood nationalism exactly like urban Indians"], ans:2, exp:"This illustrates how nationalism is not one thing but many things to different people. Urban nationalists wanted independence and constitutional rights. Tribal communities wanted freedom from forest laws restricting their traditional access to forests, protection from land alienation, and autonomy. When they heard Gandhi's message of swaraj, they heard it through their own experience — creating a localised, syncretic form of nationalism." },
  { q:"What is the significance of the Gandhi-Irwin Pact (1931)?", opts:["It gave India independence","Gandhi got everything he demanded","It showed that the colonial government was willing to negotiate with nationalist leaders — acknowledging the movement's strength — while also showing the limits of what civil disobedience could immediately achieve","It ended British rule"], ans:2, exp:"The Gandhi-Irwin Pact had mixed results: The British agreed to release political prisoners and allow salt-making in coastal areas; Gandhi agreed to suspend Civil Disobedience and attend the Round Table Conference in London. Critics (like Bhagat Singh's supporters who were executed) saw it as a sell-out. Supporters saw it as practical. Its significance: it demonstrated that mass civil disobedience could force the British to the negotiating table — a major achievement." },
  { q:"What role did print media play in spreading Indian nationalism?", opts:["Print media was only in English so did not reach Indians","The British controlled all newspapers","Vernacular newspapers (in Hindi, Bengali, Marathi, Tamil, etc.) spread nationalist ideas to millions who did not speak English — creating a shared nationalist consciousness across the country","Print media slowed nationalism"], ans:2, exp:"Vernacular press was crucial: newspapers like Kesari (Tilak, Marathi), Amrita Bazar Patrika (Bengali), The Hindu (English-Tamil) spread nationalist ideas. When the British passed the Vernacular Press Act (1878) to censor newspapers, it further radicalised editors. Nationalist newspapers created a national public sphere where people across India read and discussed the same political events." },
  { q:"Why was the concept of 'Mother India' (Bharat Mata) effective as a nationalist symbol?", opts:["It was a political concept only","It was only for Hindus","It merged religious devotion with political nationalism — people who would die for their mother (a sacred concept) would also die for Mother India — creating an emotionally powerful patriotism","It was Gandhi's personal symbol"], ans:2, exp:"Bharat Mata merged two powerful forces: motherhood (sacred in Indian culture) and political nationalism. The image transformed 'India' from an abstract geographical concept into something personal — a mother who needed to be freed from colonial oppression. This emotional framing was far more powerful than rational political arguments for many people, particularly those who were not educated but had deep religious and family values." },
  { q:"How did the Congress address the demands of workers and peasants without alienating the industrial and landlord classes?", opts:["It fully supported workers against capitalists","It supported zamindars against peasants","Congress tried to balance — sympathising with workers and peasants while reassuring industrialists and landlords that their interests would be protected — avoiding a commitment to radical class restructuring","Congress ignored workers completely"], ans:2, exp:"This was a constant tension in Congress politics. Gandhi wanted class harmony — not class conflict. He would intervene in strikes (as in Ahmedabad 1918) but asked workers to be reasonable. The Congress accepted some labour and peasant demands but stopped short of challenging the property rights of Indian industrialists and landlords who funded the movement. This class compromise shaped post-independence economic policy." },
  { q:"The Poona Pact (1932) was about:", opts:["Gandhi's arrest","A military alliance","The agreement between Gandhi and Ambedkar about reserved seats for Dalits within the general electorate — dropping the demand for separate electorates","A trade agreement"], ans:2, exp:"The Poona Pact ended Gandhi's fast-unto-death against the British plan for separate electorates for Dalits (which Gandhi saw as divisive to Hindu society). Ambedkar accepted reserved seats within the joint Hindu electorate in exchange for a larger number of reserved seats than originally proposed. The pact was controversial — Ambedkar later saw it as a betrayal of Dalit political autonomy." },
  { q:"Why were the masses receptive to Gandhi's message of non-violent civil disobedience?", opts:["Indians were naturally non-violent","Gandhi was very famous","His methods combined personal moral authority, understanding of popular religious culture, and practical tactics that even poor, illiterate people could join without needing weapons or wealth","Indians had no weapons"], ans:2, exp:"Gandhi's genius was making political action accessible: anyone could spin cotton, boycott foreign cloth, refuse to pay a tax, picket a shop. No literacy, no money, no weapons needed. His use of religious vocabulary (Ramarajya, Satya, Ahimsa) resonated with a population deeply religious in outlook. And his personal asceticism — simple clothes, fasting — gave him credibility as someone who practised what he preached." },
];

const ch2_hardMCQ = [
  { q:"ASSERTION: Gandhi's Non-Cooperation Movement was unprecedented in Indian history.\nREASON: It was the first movement to attempt to unite all sections of Indian society — Hindus, Muslims, peasants, workers, students — under one political programme.", opts:["Both A and R true; R explains A","Both true but R doesn't explain A","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both are correct. Previous nationalist movements were limited to educated elites. Gandhi's movement was revolutionary in attempting to create a genuine mass movement crossing religious, class and regional lines. The Hindu-Muslim unity of 1920-22 (Khilafat alliance) was historically unprecedented. The attempt to bring peasants, workers and tribal communities into nationalism alongside urban professionals transformed the character of Indian nationalism." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: Bhagat Singh argued that 'bombs and pistols do not make a revolution — the sword of revolution is sharpened on the whetstone of ideas'. Yet he used violence. What does this apparent contradiction reveal?", opts:["Bhagat Singh was hypocritical","He rejected ideas entirely","Bhagat Singh saw violence as a tactical tool to attract attention and spark public consciousness, not as an ideology — he believed revolutionary ideas required dramatic action to break through public indifference","He only believed in bombs"], ans:2, exp:"Bhagat Singh's violence was deliberately symbolic and theatrical: throwing bombs in the Delhi Legislative Assembly not to kill (the galleries were empty) but to 'make the deaf hear'. He wanted to force public attention on the revolutionary cause. His extensive writings (in prison) show a deeply intellectual socialist thinker. This reveals the complex relationship between ideas and action in nationalist thought — not simply dismissible as terrorism." },
  { q:"EXTRACT-BASED: 'Nationalism in India needed to create a sense of community across caste, class, religion and gender — yet each of these divisions posed a fundamental challenge.' Evaluate this statement.", opts:["Nationalism successfully united all groups","Only religion divided Indians — not caste or class","True — each division represented a different vision of what 'India' meant and who belonged, creating tensions within nationalism that Gandhi addressed only partially and that remain unresolved","Nationalism had no challenges"], ans:2, exp:"This is the central complexity of Indian nationalism. Each axis of division — caste (Dalit exclusion from temples, nationalism dominated by upper castes), class (peasants vs landlords, workers vs industrialists), religion (Hindu-Muslim tensions), gender (women fought for freedom but were expected to return to domesticity) — represented a different community with different stakes. Gandhi tried to hold these contradictions together through the concept of 'Ram Rajya' and 'swaraj' but the tensions ultimately contributed to Partition and post-independence inequalities." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: The failure of the Non-Cooperation Movement strengthened the radical wing of Indian nationalism.\nREASON: Young leaders like Bhagat Singh, Subhas Chandra Bose, and others concluded that Gandhian non-violence alone would not achieve independence.", opts:["Both A and R true; R explains A","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"The suspension of Non-Cooperation in 1922 deeply radicalised a generation. Bhagat Singh (who was a teenager in 1919-22) concluded that waiting for perfect non-violent conditions meant perpetual colonialism. Bose increasingly clashed with Gandhi's methods. The 'Swarajist' faction within Congress wanted to enter legislatures rather than boycott them. These divergences were direct responses to what they saw as Gandhi's failure to press advantage. The movement's suspension was thus paradoxically radicalising." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: Compare the participation of women in the Non-Cooperation Movement and the Civil Disobedience Movement. In what ways did women's role change?", opts:["Women did not participate in either","Women participated equally in both with no difference","Participation increased dramatically from Non-Cooperation to Civil Disobedience — from support roles to frontline picketing, salt-making, and facing police violence — representing a transformation in women's public role","Only upper-class women participated"], ans:2, exp:"This represents a significant historical shift: In Non-Cooperation (1920-22), women's participation was more limited — meetings, propaganda. In Civil Disobedience (1930s), women took frontline roles: manufacturing salt, picketing foreign cloth and liquor shops, leading processions, and going to prison. Thousands were arrested; many were beaten. Gandhi's deliberate mobilisation of women ('even more than men') was strategic and transformative. However, the political gains of independence did not always translate to social liberation at home — the contradiction between nationalist women's public courage and domestic patriarchy persisted." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: The Congress's decision to accept Dominion Status rather than complete independence at various points was a betrayal of the nationalist cause.\nREASON: Moderate Congress leaders were more afraid of radical social change than of British rule.", opts:["Both A and R true; R explains A","A is debatable rather than a fact; R has some truth — moderate leaders did fear radical social transformation more than colonial rule","A false, R true","Both false"], ans:1, exp:"This question requires nuanced evaluation. The 'betrayal' claim overstates: many Congress leaders genuinely believed incremental constitutionalism was more achievable than dramatic revolution. But the reason has merit: the Indian bourgeoisie (which dominated Congress) was more threatened by socialism and radical peasant/worker movements than by constitutional negotiations with Britain. Gandhi's own rejection of industrial capitalism and his class-harmony approach reflected these priorities. The tension between national liberation and social transformation was real and unresolved." },
  { q:"EXTRACT: 'Swaraj means not the freedom from British rule alone, but freedom from the poverty, exploitation and social injustice that British rule has perpetuated.' Which nationalist perspective does this best represent?", opts:["Gandhi's perspective only","The Muslim League's perspective","The socialist-nationalist perspective of leaders like Nehru and Bhagat Singh who insisted that political independence was meaningless without social and economic transformation","The Congress mainstream perspective"], ans:2, exp:"This perspective — political freedom must accompany social-economic freedom — was strongly held by socialists within and outside Congress. Jawaharlal Nehru's famous 'Tryst with Destiny' speech (1947) promised to end poverty along with colonialism. Bhagat Singh's socialist writings argued that replacing British capitalists with Indian capitalists was not true liberation. This perspective challenged those (Gandhi included in some interpretations) who saw swaraj primarily as moral-spiritual self-governance." },
  { q:"How does the concept of 'imagined community' apply specifically to Indian nationalism given India's extraordinary diversity?", opts:["It doesn't apply — India was not imagined","India was easy to imagine as one nation because everyone was the same","India's diversity made the imagining more complex and contested — different communities imagined 'India' differently, and creating a shared nationalist identity required deliberate cultural and political work that was never fully complete","India was united by religion alone"], ans:2, exp:"India is the ultimate test case for Benedict Anderson's theory. With hundreds of languages, multiple religions, caste hierarchies, and vast regional differences, 'India' as one nation was not natural but constructed. The INC used Hindi as a national language, the tricolour as a national flag, and figures like Gandhi as a national symbol. But different communities had different versions of 'India' — Jinnah's Muslim majority areas versus Ambedkar's Dalit India versus Gandhi's Ram Rajya. The incompleteness of this imagining contributed to Partition." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: A student asks why the British were ultimately forced to leave India in 1947 after successfully suppressing all major nationalist movements. What is the most complete explanation?", opts:["They left voluntarily out of generosity","One single movement forced them out","Multiple factors: WWII exhausted Britain economically and morally; the naval mutiny (1946) showed the military could no longer be relied on; the Cold War pressure from the USA; decades of nationalist mobilisation making India ungovernable; the international anti-colonial movement","Gandhi's fasting forced them out"], ans:2, exp:"Independence in 1947 had multiple causes working together: (1) WWII exhaustion — Britain was bankrupt, the empire financially impossible to maintain. (2) INA trials and naval mutiny — the loyalty of Indian soldiers/sailors was now in question. (3) US pressure — America was ideologically opposed to colonialism (while also being pragmatically anti-Soviet). (4) Decades of mass mobilisation — India had become increasingly difficult and expensive to govern. (5) Attlee's Labour government genuinely believed in Indian self-governance. No single factor suffices — independence was the convergence of Indian pressure and British collapse." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: Gandhi's approach to caste was fundamentally limited because he wanted to reform Hindu society without challenging the varna system.\nREASON: Gandhi accepted the principle of hereditary occupations but opposed untouchability — Ambedkar argued this approach could not end caste discrimination.", opts:["Both A and R true; R correctly explains the limitation","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"This is the central Gandhi-Ambedkar debate. Gandhi called Dalits 'Harijans' (God's people) and worked against untouchability but accepted the varna system of hereditary occupations in principle. Ambedkar argued that the varna system was the source of untouchability — you cannot end the fruit while preserving the root. Ambedkar's position was more logically consistent; Gandhi's was more politically pragmatic for maintaining upper-caste support within the nationalist movement." },
  { q:"EXTRACT-BASED: 'The Civil Disobedience Movement showed both the strength and the limits of Gandhian nationalism.' Evaluate.", opts:["It showed only strength","It showed only limits","True — it mobilised millions and forced British negotiation (strength), but failed to achieve independence and left Muslim, Dalit and working-class demands unresolved (limits)","Gandhi's methods were completely unsuccessful"], ans:2, exp:"This balanced evaluation reflects historical consensus. Strengths: unprecedented mass mobilisation including women; forced the Gandhi-Irwin Pact; demonstrated India was ungovernable without consent; built a national movement. Limits: did not achieve independence; Muslim participation declined; Dalit demands unaddressed; ultimately suspended (1931, 1934) without achieving stated goals. The movement demonstrated that mass civil disobedience could pressure but not compel the British — independence required WWII to make it economically and politically necessary for Britain." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: Why did the Second Round Table Conference (1931) fail? What does this reveal about the possibilities and limits of constitutional negotiation?", opts:["Gandhi did not attend","The British refused all discussion","Gandhi attended but found British unwilling to grant self-governance while simultaneously being pressured by Muslim League, Princes, and Ambedkar for separate representations — revealing that 'Indian nationalism' was not one unified demand but multiple competing claims","Gandhi was arrested at the conference"], ans:2, exp:"The Round Table Conference failure revealed a structural problem: 'India' at the negotiating table was not one voice but many — Congress (claiming to represent all of India), Muslim League (claiming to represent Muslims separately), Princes (defending their territories), Ambedkar (claiming to represent Dalits). The British cleverly used these divisions to argue that no single group could speak for 'India'. This is why constitutional negotiations kept failing while mass movements kept growing — the political problem was not solvable by negotiation alone." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: The Indian nationalism of the 1920s-1930s was fundamentally different from the nationalism of the earlier Congress period (1885-1905).\nREASON: It transformed from an elite constitutional movement into a mass movement involving peasants, workers, women and even tribal communities.", opts:["Both A and R true; R explains the difference","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"This periodisation is standard historical analysis. Early Congress (1885-1905) was dominated by English-educated professionals, met annually to pass resolutions, and humbly petitioned the British for constitutional reforms. Gandhi's nationalism (1919-42) was a mass phenomenon — millions participated, including people who could not read English, did not attend Congress sessions, but understood Gandhi's simple symbolic language. This qualitative transformation made independence possible where previous elite petitioning had failed." },
  { q:"What is the historical significance of the 'October 1943 famine in Bengal' in the context of Indian nationalism?", opts:["The famine helped British rule","The famine was a natural disaster unrelated to politics","The famine — caused by British wartime policies of food export and deliberate denial of relief — killing 2-3 million people — revealed the fatal cost of colonial extraction and radicalised Indian opposition to British rule in its final phase","Indians caused the famine themselves"], ans:2, exp:"The 1943 Bengal Famine (under Churchill's wartime government) was caused by: export of food from India for the British war effort; denial of famine relief; destruction of boats to prevent Japanese invasion. Around 3 million people died. This man-made disaster under colonial rule powerfully illustrated the argument that British rule was literally killing Indians — and strengthened the argument that independence was not just a political aspiration but a matter of physical survival." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: Evaluate why Partition (1947) represents both the success and failure of Indian nationalism.", opts:["Partition was only a success","Partition was only a failure","Partition was both: nationalism succeeded in ending British rule but failed to create a unified nation — the nationalism that sought to transcend religious divisions ultimately produced a religious partition, revealing the limits of Congress's claim to represent all Indians","Partition had nothing to do with nationalism"], ans:2, exp:"This is the central tragic irony of Indian nationalism. The movement that began with the slogan of Hindu-Muslim unity ended in religious partition and mass communal violence. Congress nationalism claimed to represent all Indians; the Muslim League argued that Congress represented Hindu interests. The failure to resolve the tension between territorial nationalism and religious identity resulted in two nations instead of one — independence and partition simultaneously. Whether partition was inevitable or avoidable remains the most debated question in South Asian history." },
];


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// CH 3 — THE MAKING OF A GLOBAL WORLD
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

const ch3_pyqs = [
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"What is globalisation? How was the pre-modern world already 'connected' before the 19th century?", answer:"Globalisation refers to the integration of economies, cultures and societies across the world through trade, migration, communication and capital flows. Pre-modern connections: (1) Silk Routes — linked Asia with Europe and Africa, carrying silk, spices, pottery and ideas for over a millennium. (2) India and China were centres of global trade for 1,500 years before Europe's rise. (3) Marco Polo and others brought knowledge of Asian wealth to Europe, inspiring exploration. (4) Disease as globalisation — the bubonic plague (1347) spread from China through Central Asia to Europe via trade routes, killing one-third of Europe's population — showing how connected the pre-modern world was. (5) Food crops — potatoes, tomatoes, maize from the Americas transformed diets globally after 1500. (6) Gold and silver from the Americas transformed Asian trade.", year:2023, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"How did the discovery of America affect the economies of Europe and the rest of the world?", answer:"The discovery of America (1492) had transformative global effects: (1) Gold and silver — massive quantities flowed from mines in Peru and Mexico to Spain and Portugal, then to Asia to pay for spice trade. This transformed Asian economies and caused inflation in Europe. (2) New food crops — potatoes, tomatoes, maize, sweet potatoes reached Europe, Asia and Africa, transformed diets, supported population growth. The potato alone is credited with ending famines in Europe. (3) The slave trade — millions of Africans were transported to Americas for plantation labour, creating a brutal transatlantic economy. (4) The destruction of indigenous civilisations — disease (smallpox) killed 90%+ of indigenous American populations. (5) Colonial plantation economies — created systems of coerced labour that produced cotton, tobacco, sugar for European markets.", year:2023, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"What was the Corn Laws controversy in Britain? How did its repeal affect global trade?", answer:"The Corn Laws imposed import duties on foreign grain (corn) to protect British landlords and farmers. Working people in cities opposed them as they kept food prices high. Repeal (1846): (1) Grain could now be freely imported from Eastern Europe, Russia, and later America and Australia. (2) This made food cheaper in Britain — benefiting workers and industrialists. (3) It began the era of British free trade. Global effects: (1) Britain became dependent on imported food. (2) Eastern European and American farmers expanded cultivation to supply Britain. (3) This connected food producers in Russia, Argentina and Australia to British consumers. (4) When cheaper American grain entered markets in the 1870s-80s, Eastern European landlords suffered — generating political reactions including calls for re-imposition of tariffs.", year:2022, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"What was the role of the 'indentured labour' system in the 19th-century global economy?", answer:"Indentured labour was a form of bonded labour where workers signed contracts to work for a fixed period (usually 5 years) in exchange for passage to a new country. Context: After slavery was abolished in British colonies (1833), plantation owners in Caribbean, South Africa, Fiji and Mauritius needed labour. They recruited from India (Bihar, UP, Tamil Nadu) and China. Conditions: (1) Workers were transported to distant places — often under false pretences. (2) Living conditions were harsh — poor housing, long hours, brutal punishments. (3) Workers were called 'coolie' — a derogatory term. (4) Return was extremely difficult. (5) Wages were minimal. Indian nationalist leaders condemned it as 'new slavery'. Gandhi's campaigns in South Africa began partly over treatment of indentured Indian workers. The system ended in 1921.", year:2022, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"How did the First World War transform the global economy?", answer:"WWI (1914-18) transformed the global economy in several ways: (1) The war required massive industrial production — governments borrowed heavily and printed money, causing inflation. (2) Britain — the centre of pre-war globalisation — emerged heavily indebted to the USA. The financial centre of the world shifted from London to New York. (3) Agricultural production expanded enormously during the war (to feed armies) — when the war ended, prices collapsed as demand fell, devastating farmers. (4) Industries shifted to war production — disrupting civilian supply chains. (5) Post-war reconstruction created a brief boom in 1920s America. (6) The war destroyed the pre-war system of international trade and finance. (7) US emerged as the world's largest creditor nation.", year:2021, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"What is the Great Depression? What were its causes and global effects?", answer:"The Great Depression (1929-39) was the worst economic crisis of the 20th century. Causes: (1) The Wall Street Crash (October 1929) — US stock market collapsed. (2) Banks called in loans, creating a banking crisis. (3) Deflation — falling prices reduced investment. (4) Overproduction — particularly in agriculture. (5) High tariffs worldwide reduced trade. Global effects: (1) US industrial production fell by 50%, unemployment reached 25%. (2) US banks recalled loans from Europe — causing European banking crises. (3) Agricultural prices collapsed worldwide — devastating primary producers in Asia, Africa and Latin America. (4) India's exports fell; farmers were ruined. (5) Political radicalisation — Hitler rose to power in Germany partly through exploiting Depression grievances.", year:2021, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"How did the Great Depression affect India?", answer:"Effects on India: (1) Agricultural prices fell 50% — Indian farmers who had taken loans could not repay them. (2) India was a major exporter of agricultural products (wheat, cotton, jute) — these prices collapsed. (3) As the British government was committed to the gold standard, it forced India to export gold to stabilise sterling — draining India's gold reserves. (4) Peasant indebtedness increased massively — zamindars squeezed farmers for rent even as crop prices fell. (5) Urban unemployment increased as industries contracted. (6) The Civil Disobedience Movement (1930) was partly energised by peasant misery — the Depression was a context for Gandhi's Salt March. (7) Indian industrial production was also hit as demand fell.", year:2020, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"What was the Bretton Woods Agreement? How did it shape the post-WWII global economy?", answer:"Bretton Woods (July 1944): Meeting in New Hampshire, USA, 44 nations established the post-war international financial system. Key decisions: (1) IMF (International Monetary Fund) — to stabilise exchange rates and provide short-term loans to countries with balance of payments problems. (2) World Bank — to provide long-term development loans. (3) Dollar linked to gold — US dollar became the global reserve currency at $35 per ounce of gold. (4) Fixed exchange rates — currencies pegged to the dollar. Impact: (1) Created stability that enabled 25 years of unprecedented economic growth (1945-70). (2) US became the dominant global economic power. (3) Developing countries were represented but marginally — the system reflected Western (primarily American) interests. (4) This 'Bretton Woods era' ended in 1971 when Nixon ended dollar-gold convertibility.", year:2020, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"What were the Silk Routes? How did they contribute to global cultural and commercial exchange?", answer:"The Silk Routes (3rd century BCE - 15th century CE) were an extensive network of trade routes connecting China, Central Asia, Persia, Arabia and the Mediterranean. Commercial exchanges: (1) China exported silk (hence the name), porcelain, tea. (2) India exported spices, cotton, pepper, indigo. (3) Rome exported gold, silver, glass, wine. (4) The routes operated both by land (Central Asian routes) and sea (Indian Ocean routes). Cultural exchanges: (1) Buddhism spread from India to China, Korea, Japan via these routes. (2) Islam spread along trade routes across Asia and Africa. (3) Paper and printing technology moved from China westward. (4) Diseases (including the plague) also travelled these routes. The routes were not a single road but a web of connected paths, bringing the world together through commerce and ideas.", year:2019, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"How did the invention of refrigeration change global trade patterns?", answer:"Refrigeration transformed global food trade: (1) Before refrigeration, only preserved foods (dried, salted, tinned) could be traded long-distance. (2) Refrigeration technology (from 1870s) allowed fresh and frozen meat to be transported from Argentina and Australia to Britain. (3) The first refrigerated ship carried meat from Argentina to France in 1877. (4) This transformed global agriculture — countries like Argentina and Australia became major meat exporters. (5) Meat prices fell in Europe — working-class families could afford meat for the first time. (6) The technology incentivised clearing land in Argentina and Australia for cattle ranching, displacing indigenous peoples. (7) It linked distant agricultural producers directly to European consumers.", year:2019, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2023", question:"Explain the factors that led to the globalisation of the 19th century world economy.", answer:"19th century globalisation was driven by: (1) Industrial Revolution — Britain's industrial capitalism needed raw materials from colonies and markets for manufactured goods worldwide. (2) Free trade — abolition of Corn Laws (1846), British free trade policy opened global markets. (3) Transport revolution — steam railways reduced land transport costs dramatically; steamships crossed oceans faster. (4) Communications — the electric telegraph (1860s) connected continents; messages that took weeks to travel now took seconds. (5) Capital export — British banks financed railways, mines and plantations worldwide. (6) Migration — 50 million Europeans emigrated to Americas and Australia; millions of Indians and Chinese were sent as indentured labourers. (7) The Gold Standard — stable exchange rates under the gold standard facilitated international trade.", year:2023, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2022", question:"What is the 'gold standard' and how did Britain's commitment to it worsen the Great Depression?", answer:"The gold standard was a system where a country's currency was directly convertible into gold at a fixed rate. Britain returned to the gold standard in 1925 to restore pre-war financial prestige. How it worsened the Depression: (1) It prevented governments from expanding money supply to stimulate the economy (as any money printed had to be backed by gold reserves). (2) Countries on the gold standard were forced to raise interest rates and cut spending when they should have been doing the opposite. (3) When the US banking crisis spread, countries on the gold standard were dragged into it. (4) When Britain left the gold standard in 1931, those countries whose currencies were pegged to sterling (including India) lost gold reserves as sterling depreciated. Countries that left the gold standard earlier (like Britain 1931) recovered faster than those that stayed on it (like USA until 1933).", year:2022, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2021", question:"How did the post-WWII international institutions reflect the vision of 'regulated capitalism'?", answer:"Post-WWII international institutions (Bretton Woods system) were designed to prevent a repeat of the 1930s economic nationalism and Depression. Regulated capitalism features: (1) IMF and World Bank provided stability and development finance — replacing unregulated pre-war financial flows. (2) Fixed exchange rates (rather than competitive devaluation as in 1930s). (3) Capital controls allowed governments to regulate financial flows — preventing speculation. (4) Recognition that governments must intervene to ensure employment and welfare (Keynesian economics). (5) Full employment became the primary economic goal. (6) The model worked — 1945-70 saw unprecedented growth, stable currencies, rising wages. The irony: this 'regulated capitalism' proved highly successful, suggesting that pure free markets needed management to prevent the boom-bust cycles that had caused such misery.", year:2021, marks:5, difficulty:"hard" },
  { title:"PYQ 2020", question:"What is meant by 'de-industrialisation' in the context of Indian economic history?", answer:"De-industrialisation refers to the decline of India's traditional industries during British colonial rule. Process: (1) British machine-made goods (especially cotton textiles) flooded India after the Industrial Revolution. (2) British textiles were cheaper and drove Indian handloom weavers out of business. (3) The British removed tariffs protecting Indian industries while maintaining high tariffs for Indian goods entering Britain. (4) India was reduced from a major exporter of manufactured goods (Dhaka muslin, Surat cotton) to primarily an exporter of raw materials. (5) Indian artisans — weavers, metal workers — lost livelihoods. (6) Indian towns that had been manufacturing centres declined. This is why Gandhi's charkha (spinning wheel) became such a powerful symbol — it directly challenged British de-industrialisation of India.", year:2020, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
  { title:"PYQ 2019", question:"Why did some economists and politicians support protectionism rather than free trade in the late 19th century?", answer:"Arguments for protectionism: (1) British free trade was actually British imperialism — the UK was the most industrialised country and benefited most from free trade while forcing open markets of less developed countries. (2) Germany and USA used tariffs to protect their emerging industries from British competition (infant industry argument). (3) Friedrich List's 'national economy' theory — developing economies need protection to build their industries before competing with advanced ones. (4) Agricultural lobbies in continental Europe demanded protection when cheap American grain undercut their prices. (5) Employment protection — free trade could destroy domestic industries and create unemployment. By the 1880s, Germany, France and USA had all adopted protective tariffs, undermining British free-trade ideology.", year:2019, marks:3, difficulty:"medium" },
];

const ch3_easyMCQ = [
  { q:"The Silk Routes primarily connected which regions?", opts:["Africa and Europe","China, Central Asia and the Mediterranean","India and the Americas","Australia and Asia"], ans:1, exp:"The Silk Routes connected China (silk, porcelain) through Central Asia to the Mediterranean and Europe. They were a network of land and sea routes operating from roughly 3rd century BCE to 15th century CE, facilitating trade in goods, ideas and disease." },
  { q:"Which food crops came to the world from the Americas after 1492?", opts:["Rice, wheat, barley","Potatoes, tomatoes, maize, sweet potatoes","Spices like pepper and cinnamon","Sugar and coffee"], ans:1, exp:"Potatoes, tomatoes, maize (corn) and sweet potatoes were all American crops unknown elsewhere before Columbus. The potato particularly transformed European food supply — some historians credit it with ending the famines that had periodically devastated Europe." },
  { q:"Indentured labour was called 'new slavery' because:", opts:["Workers were paid no wages","Workers were branded","Workers signed contracts under false pretences and worked in conditions very similar to slavery — restricted movement, bonded to employers, brutal punishments","Workers were from Africa"], ans:2, exp:"Indentured workers were recruited from poor rural areas with promises of good wages and conditions that rarely materialised. Once in distant plantations (Caribbean, Fiji, South Africa), they could not leave — they were bonded by their contracts. Indian nationalists and Gandhi campaigned against it as a form of slavery with legal paperwork." },
  { q:"What caused the Wall Street Crash of 1929?", opts:["A natural disaster","Overspeculation in stock markets led to a collapse in share prices","A world war","A banking fraud"], ans:1, exp:"The Wall Street Crash (October 1929) was triggered by rampant speculation — people had bought shares on credit ('buying on margin') and when prices started falling, panic selling created a crash. Share prices fell by 80%. Banks that had lent money for speculation collapsed. This triggered the Great Depression." },
  { q:"The Bretton Woods conference established which institutions?", opts:["United Nations and NATO","IMF and World Bank","WHO and WTO","G7 and G20"], ans:1, exp:"The Bretton Woods Conference (1944) established the IMF (International Monetary Fund) to stabilise exchange rates and provide emergency loans, and the World Bank to fund long-term development. These institutions shaped the post-WWII global economy and continue operating today." },
  { q:"The repeal of the Corn Laws in Britain (1846) resulted in:", opts:["Higher food prices","Britain stopping all imports","Cheaper food imports, lower bread prices, and the beginning of an era of British free trade","End of British agriculture"], ans:2, exp:"Repealing the Corn Laws (tariffs on grain) meant foreign grain could enter Britain freely. Bread prices fell — benefiting workers. It marked Britain's shift to free trade policy, opening its markets to global agricultural products in exchange for markets for its manufactured goods." },
  { q:"The Panama Canal and Suez Canal were significant because:", opts:["They were tourist attractions","They dramatically shortened sea routes, reducing shipping costs and accelerating global trade","They were military fortifications","They were sources of fresh water"], ans:1, exp:"Both canals dramatically shortened shipping routes: the Suez Canal (1869) cut the Europe-Asia journey by thousands of miles; the Panama Canal (1914) shortened the route between Atlantic and Pacific. Reduced shipping costs made global trade more economical, accelerating 19th-century globalisation." },
  { q:"What was the Gold Standard?", opts:["A set of rules about gold jewellery","A system where currency values were fixed in terms of gold — maintaining stable exchange rates","A prize given to the best economy","A trade agreement about gold imports"], ans:1, exp:"Under the Gold Standard, each country fixed its currency's value in gold. This created stable exchange rates between countries. Britain was on the gold standard from 1870s, left in 1931 during the Depression. The stability it created facilitated international trade and investment." },
  { q:"Dhaka muslin was famous because:", opts:["It was very cheap","It was so fine it was called 'woven air' — and India was a major exporter before British de-industrialisation destroyed Indian textiles","It was made by machines","It was imported from France"], ans:1, exp:"Dhaka (Bangladesh) muslin was so extraordinarily fine it was known by names like 'woven air' or 'running water'. Indian textile craftsmanship was world-renowned. British machine-made cotton systematically destroyed this craft tradition in the 19th century — de-industrialisation." },
  { q:"The Great Depression began in which country?", opts:["Germany","France","USA","Britain"], ans:2, exp:"The Great Depression began with the Wall Street Crash in the USA (October 1929). American banks then recalled loans from Europe, spreading the crisis globally. Because America had become the world's largest economy and lender, its financial collapse dragged the whole world into depression." },
  { q:"What is 'free trade'?", opts:["Trade without any products","Trade between friends only","Trade without tariffs, quotas or government restrictions — allowing goods to move freely across borders","Trade of free goods"], ans:2, exp:"Free trade means removing tariffs (import taxes), quotas and other restrictions so goods can move across borders based purely on price and demand. Britain promoted free trade from the 1840s as it was the world's most efficient manufacturer. Less developed countries resisted as free trade could destroy their emerging industries." },
  { q:"Rinderpest was:", opts:["A type of cloth","A cattle disease that devastated African cattle herds in the 1890s, destroying livelihoods and forcing Africans into colonial wage labour","A type of railway line","A gold mine"], ans:1, exp:"Rinderpest was a fast-spreading cattle plague that arrived in Africa in the 1890s (through cattle imported for Italian military in Eritrea). It killed 90% of cattle in eastern and southern Africa within years, destroying pastoralist and farming communities' livelihoods and making them dependent on wage labour in colonial mines and farms." },
  { q:"The first country to industrialise was:", opts:["France","Germany","USA","Britain"], ans:3, exp:"Britain was the first country to industrialise (Industrial Revolution, 1760s-1840s). Britain had coal, iron ore, rivers for power, a colonial empire for raw materials and markets, and a culture of technical innovation. This gave Britain a huge economic lead that it used to dominate global trade through the 19th century." },
  { q:"G-77 refers to:", opts:["A car model","A group of 77 developing nations that came together to demand a New International Economic Order in the 1970s","A military alliance","A trade agreement between 77 countries"], ans:1, exp:"G-77 (Group of 77) was formed in the 1960s-70s by developing nations who felt the Bretton Woods system was designed to serve Western interests. They demanded a 'New International Economic Order' — fairer terms of trade, technology transfer and debt relief. It reflected post-colonial nations' recognition that political independence had not brought economic equality." },
  { q:"What was the significance of the electric telegraph in 19th-century globalisation?", opts:["It carried electricity to homes","It connected continents — messages that took weeks by ship now took seconds, transforming business, news and diplomatic communication globally","It was used for lighting streets","It was a type of railway signal"], ans:1, exp:"The electric telegraph (from 1860s) was the internet of the 19th century. The transatlantic telegraph cable (1866) connected Europe and America instantaneously. Businesses could receive commodity prices from around the world; governments could send orders to distant colonies; newspapers could publish foreign news the same day. It was a revolutionary compression of time and space." },
];

const ch3_mediumMCQ = [
  { q:"Why is it said that the 'discovery' of America caused the destruction of its indigenous civilisations?", opts:["Wars only killed the indigenous people","Spanish conquests brought diseases — especially smallpox — to which indigenous people had no immunity, killing an estimated 90% of the population","Indigenous people voluntarily left","Europeans only came for gold and left"], ans:1, exp:"The Spanish conquest of the Americas from 1492 brought European diseases — especially smallpox, measles, and influenza — against which the indigenous population had no immunity. Epidemiologists estimate that 50-90% of indigenous Americans died within a century of European contact. This demographic collapse made conquest possible and destroyed civilisations that had existed for millennia." },
  { q:"How did the Atlantic slave trade transform both Africa and the Americas?", opts:["It had no lasting effects","It enriched Africa","It destroyed West African societies (depopulation, warfare, state collapse) while creating plantation economies in the Americas based on forced labour that produced cotton, sugar and tobacco for European markets","Slavery was beneficial for all sides"], ans:2, exp:"The slave trade had catastrophic and transformative effects on both regions. West Africa lost 12-15 million people over 300 years — primarily young adults, its most productive members. It destabilised politics (coastal states raided inland ones for slaves). In the Americas, slave plantations produced enormous wealth for European elites while denying Africans their humanity and rights. The legacy of slavery continues to shape racial inequalities in the Americas today." },
  { q:"What is the connection between the abolition of slavery and the rise of indentured labour?", opts:["They were unrelated","The abolition of slavery created a labour shortage in plantation colonies — plantation owners found indentured labour as a substitute, creating a new form of coerced labour that could survive abolition","Indentured workers replaced slaves immediately","The British government organised both systems separately"], ans:1, exp:"When slavery was abolished in British colonies (1833), plantation owners in the Caribbean, Mauritius, South Africa and Fiji needed workers. They turned to 'indentured' contracts from India and China — nominally voluntary and paid, but practically coercive given poverty, deception in recruitment, and harsh conditions once workers arrived far from home. Indian nationalists called it 'new slavery' for good reason." },
  { q:"How did the construction of railways in the 19th century transform global trade?", opts:["Railways were only for passengers","Railways had no economic impact","Railways dramatically reduced land transport costs — opening up interiors of continents (USA, India, Canada, Argentina, Russia) to commercial agriculture, connecting mines to ports, and enabling large-scale international trade in bulky goods like grain and coal","Railways only worked within cities"], ans:2, exp:"Railways were the key infrastructure of 19th-century globalisation. Before railways, transporting grain across a continent was prohibitively expensive. With railways, American and Indian wheat could reach Atlantic ports cheaply. British capital financed railways worldwide — connecting colonised territories to global markets and making colonialism profitable. Railways also transformed warfare, social life and national integration." },
  { q:"What was the 'scramble for Africa' and how did it relate to the global economy?", opts:["A gold rush in Africa","The 1884-1914 partition of Africa among European powers, driven by competition for raw materials, markets and strategic territory","A sporting event","A migration of Africans to Europe"], ans:1, exp:"Between 1884-1914, European powers partitioned almost the entire African continent among themselves (Berlin Conference 1884 set the rules). Causes: (1) Industrial capitalism needed raw materials — African minerals, rubber, cotton. (2) Competition between European powers for global power and prestige. (3) Belief in racial superiority ('white man's burden'). (4) Strategic interest in controlling sea routes (Suez Canal, Cape route to India). Africa went from 10% European control in 1880 to 90% by 1914." },
  { q:"Why did the Bretton Woods system eventually collapse in 1971?", opts:["The IMF ran out of money","Cold War tensions destroyed it","The USA could no longer maintain the gold-dollar link — it had printed too many dollars to finance the Vietnam War and Great Society programmes, so Nixon ended dollar-gold convertibility, causing floating exchange rates","The World Bank failed"], ans:2, exp:"The Bretton Woods system required the US to maintain $35/ounce of gold. But by the 1960s, there were far more dollars circulating globally than US gold reserves could back (partly from Vietnam War spending). European countries began redeeming dollars for gold, threatening US reserves. Nixon ended dollar-gold convertibility in 1971 ('Nixon Shock'), and exchange rates became floating. This ended the Bretton Woods era but not the IMF/World Bank." },
  { q:"Why did the Great Depression cause political radicalisation in Europe?", opts:["The Depression made people conservative","Poverty and unemployment made millions desperate, creating the conditions for fascism (Hitler in Germany, Mussolini in Italy) as people sought radical solutions to economic collapse","The Depression only affected the USA","Politicians prevented radicalisation"], ans:1, exp:"The Depression destroyed the middle classes and created mass unemployment. In Germany, unemployment reached 30%+ by 1932. Hitler offered simple explanations (Jews, Communists, the Versailles Treaty) and radical solutions (rearmament, national pride, expansion). The German democratic republic (Weimar) could not solve the economic crisis and lost legitimacy. This is how economic catastrophe creates political catastrophe — the Depression's political legacy was WWII." },
  { q:"What is meant by 'reparations' and how did they contribute to the economic instability of the 1920s-30s?", opts:["Repairs to war damage","The war debts Germany was forced to pay under the Treaty of Versailles — creating economic instability that contributed to hyperinflation, resentment and eventually Hitler's rise","A type of trade agreement","Foreign aid given to Germany"], ans:1, exp:"Under the Treaty of Versailles (1919), Germany was forced to accept war guilt and pay 132 billion gold marks in reparations. Germany could not pay from its own resources and borrowed US money. When the US banking crisis hit in 1929, American banks called in their loans to Germany — Germany's economy collapsed. The reparations system thus created an economically fragile Germany and contributed to the conditions that brought Hitler to power." },
  { q:"How did post-WWII decolonisation change the global economic order?", opts:["Decolonisation improved the global economy immediately","New nations had full economic independence","Formal political independence was not accompanied by economic independence — former colonies remained dependent on selling raw materials at low prices to former colonial powers (neo-colonialism)","Decolonisation ended all economic relationships between former colonies and powers"], ans:2, exp:"This is the concept of 'neo-colonialism': after political independence, the economic structure of the colonial relationship often persisted. New nations still exported raw materials (cotton, minerals, coffee, cocoa) and imported manufactured goods — the same trade pattern as under colonialism but now through 'free market' mechanisms. The terms of trade consistently favoured manufactured goods over raw materials, keeping former colonies economically weak. This is why the G-77 demanded a 'New International Economic Order'." },
  { q:"What is the significance of the potato in European history?", opts:["It was used as currency","The potato, introduced from America after 1492, transformed European food supply — high-calorie, easy to grow — supporting population growth and reducing famine deaths across Europe", "It caused major wars in Europe","Potatoes were only eaten by the rich"], ans:1, exp:"The potato (from the Andes, Peru) arrived in Europe in the late 16th century. It was revolutionary: (1) More calories per acre than any grain. (2) Could be grown in poor soil. (3) Easy storage. The Irish Famine (1845-49) was caused by potato blight, killing 1 million and causing 2 million to emigrate — paradoxically demonstrating how dependent Europe had become on this American crop by the 19th century." },
  { q:"What does 'capital export' mean and how did it contribute to 19th-century globalisation?", opts:["Exporting money from the country","British and European banks investing surplus capital (profits from industry) in overseas railways, mines, plantations and infrastructure — financing globalisation while expecting profitable returns","Sending gold to other countries as gifts","Capital export was only done by the USA"], ans:1, exp:"By the 19th century, British industry had generated enormous profits. Rather than reinvesting all in Britain, these surplus funds were exported to finance railways in India (£160 million), Argentina, Australia and USA. This British capital export financed global infrastructure that connected colonial raw material producers to European markets — simultaneously building globalisation and making enormous profits for British investors." },
  { q:"Why did the US avoid taking on the role of international financial leadership after WWI that Britain had played before the war?", opts:["The US was too poor","US isolationism — the US emerged from WWI as the world's largest economy and creditor but retreated into political isolationism, refusing to stabilise the global economy, contributing to the instability of the 1920s-30s","The US had no gold","The US preferred the gold standard"], ans:1, exp:"This is the interwar paradox. The USA became the world's dominant economy after WWI but refused the international responsibilities that came with it. Congress rejected Woodrow Wilson's League of Nations; the US raised tariffs (Smoot-Hawley 1930) instead of leading free trade; it recalled loans from Europe during the Depression rather than extending credit. Britain could no longer stabilise the global economy; the US would not. This vacuum of leadership is why the Depression became a global catastrophe." },
  { q:"How did indentured Indian workers maintain their cultural identity in distant colonies?", opts:["They adopted local cultures entirely","They abandoned Indian culture","They created hybrid cultures combining Indian traditions with local influences — languages, music, food, festivals evolved. Indian communities in Trinidad, Fiji, South Africa, Mauritius maintain distinct Indo-Caribbean/Indo-Fijian cultures to this day","Cultural identity was banned in colonies"], ans:2, exp:"Cultural adaptation in diaspora created fascinating hybrid cultures. Trinidad's chutney music, Fiji's Indo-Fijian Hindi dialect, South Africa's Cape Malay cuisine — all emerge from the cultural creativity of transported communities who maintained Indian cultural roots while adapting to new environments. The great-grandchildren of indentured workers became important figures in these countries' independence movements (like Gandhi in South Africa)." },
  { q:"What is the relationship between the Suez Canal (1869) and British imperialism?", opts:["The canal was irrelevant to imperialism","The Suez Canal was a purely commercial project","The canal dramatically shortened the route from Britain to India — reducing the journey from 3 months to 3 weeks — making the British Empire in Asia more profitable and militarily controllable, intensifying the economic relationship between metropolis and colony","The canal was built by France alone"], ans:2, exp:"The Suez Canal was transformative for the British Empire. The route from Britain to India was cut from 3 months (Cape of Good Hope) to 3 weeks. This made the Indian Empire far more profitable (cheaper to extract resources, cheaper to garrison) and integrated into the British economy. Egypt was acquired by Britain in 1882 largely to control the Canal. The Canal symbolised how industrial-age infrastructure both enabled and depended on imperialism." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: A development economist argues that 'the Bretton Woods system reflected the power of the victors of WWII, not a genuinely equitable global system.' Evaluate.", opts:["The Bretton Woods system was perfectly fair","Developing countries were not yet independent in 1944","True — the USA and UK designed Bretton Woods to serve their interests: dollar as reserve currency benefited USA; conditionalities on IMF loans reflected Western views; developing countries had little voice — but the system also provided genuine stability that enabled growth worldwide","The system was only harmful"], ans:2, exp:"Bretton Woods was simultaneously genuinely beneficial (stability, growth) and reflective of power. The dollar's reserve currency status gave the USA enormous economic privilege — it could run deficits other countries couldn't. IMF conditionalities often required painful austerity from borrowing countries regardless of context. Developing countries' interests were not prioritised. Yet the stability of 1945-70 was real. This is the complexity — Bretton Woods served Western interests while also providing global goods like stability." },
];

const ch3_hardMCQ = [
  { q:"ASSERTION: The 19th-century globalisation was fundamentally different from medieval globalisation.\nREASON: Industrial capitalism required systematic, large-scale integration of global markets for raw materials and finished goods — not just the luxury trade of the Silk Routes.", opts:["Both A and R true; R correctly explains the difference","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Both are correct. Medieval globalisation (Silk Routes) was primarily luxury trade — silk, spices, gold — for elites. Industrial globalisation was mass economic integration: British factories needed millions of tonnes of cotton from India and America; millions of workers' basic needs (bread, cotton clothing) depended on global supply chains. The scale, depth and necessity of integration was fundamentally different." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: How does the concept of 'comparative advantage' explain 19th century trade patterns and why has it been criticised?", opts:["It fully explains trade perfectly","Comparative advantage theory says countries should specialise in what they produce most efficiently — but critics note it justified Britain's forcing colonies to specialise in raw materials rather than develop industries, permanently disadvantaging them","Comparative advantage was not used in the 19th century","Only Ricardo developed this theory later"], ans:1, exp:"David Ricardo's comparative advantage theory was used to justify the colonial trade structure: India should grow cotton (its comparative advantage) and import British cloth (Britain's comparative advantage in manufacturing). Critics (List in Germany, economic nationalists everywhere) argued this locked developing regions into primary commodity production permanently, preventing industrial development. The USA and Germany ignored comparative advantage and used tariffs to build their industries." },
  { q:"EXTRACT-BASED: 'The Great Depression demonstrated that free markets left to themselves produce catastrophic outcomes.' How does the evidence of the 1929-39 period support this?", opts:["Free markets solved the Depression quickly","Government intervention made the Depression worse","True — the Depression showed: market crashes spiral without intervention; banking panics destroy credit systems; unemployment persists without stimulus; deflation creates feedback loops — all requiring government intervention that Keynesian economics subsequently provided","Free markets are always optimal"], ans:2, exp:"The Depression was the key evidence for Keynesian economics. The 'automatic' market recovery that classical economists promised did not happen — unemployment remained at 25% for years. Countries that intervened (Roosevelt's New Deal in USA, Germany's rearmament spending, Sweden's social democratic policies) recovered faster than those that applied austerity. This experience directly shaped the Bretton Woods consensus that markets needed managed stability." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: Post-WWII decolonisation created politically independent but economically dependent nations.\nREASON: The structure of colonial economic exploitation (raw materials exported, manufactured goods imported) persisted after independence through 'terms of trade' that consistently favoured manufactured goods.", opts:["Both A and R true; R explains why economic dependence persisted","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"This is the neo-colonial theory. Independence transferred political control to new national elites but the economic structure was unchanged. Ghana still exported cocoa; India still exported cotton; Congo still exported copper — at prices set in London or New York. The terms of trade (ratio of export to import prices) consistently moved against primary commodities, meaning former colonies had to export more and more to import the same manufactured goods. This structural inequality is the lasting legacy of colonialism." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: Compare the first globalisation (1870-1913) and the second globalisation (post-1990). What are the key similarities and differences?", opts:["They are identical","First was only about trade; second only about services","Similarities: capital flows, migration, technology transfer, trade growth. Differences: first was driven by British power and colonial extraction; second is driven by US power and multinational corporations; first featured more labour migration; second features more financial capital flows and digital services","There is no comparison to make"], ans:2, exp:"Both globalisations share structural features (integration, capital flows, technology spread) but differ fundamentally in political economy. First globalisation was colonial — capital exported from core to periphery for raw material extraction; migration was massive (50M Europeans emigrated). Second globalisation is post-colonial but dominated by multinational corporations; migration is restricted; financial flows dwarf trade flows; services (banking, IT) are as important as manufacturing. Both created inequality within countries while reducing some between-country inequality." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: Gandhi's charkha (spinning wheel) campaign was economically irrational but politically powerful.\nREASON: Machine-made cloth was cheaper than handspun, but the charkha directly challenged the colonial economic logic that had destroyed Indian textile industries.", opts:["Both A and R true; R correctly explains the political power despite economic irrationality","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"Gandhi explicitly accepted that machine cloth was cheaper. His campaign was not about economic efficiency — it was about economic agency and anti-colonialism. The charkha said: India will determine its own economic life; we will make our own cloth even if it costs more; we refuse to be a market for British goods and a supplier of raw cotton. This economic nationalism challenged the colonial economic structure at its core. The 'economic irrationality' was precisely the political point." },
  { q:"EXTRACT: 'The free trade era was not really free — it was British imperialism with good marketing.' Evaluate this statement.", opts:["Free trade was genuinely free for all","Britain was the only country that practised free trade while using its navy and colonial power to pry open others' markets — making it a system that benefited the already-industrialised at the expense of the developing","All countries benefited equally from free trade","Free trade existed before Britain"], ans:1, exp:"This critique has significant historical basis. Britain adopted free trade when it was already the world's most efficient manufacturer — it was in Britain's economic interest. When Britain 'encouraged' India to reduce tariffs on British textiles while maintaining barriers on Indian goods entering Britain, 'free trade' became a tool of colonial extraction. Germany, USA, and France adopted tariffs to protect their developing industries — often with greater long-term success. Free trade theory served British interests particularly well." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: How did WWI end British financial hegemony and create the conditions for American hegemony?", opts:["WWI had no effect on financial power","Britain became stronger after WWI","WWI forced Britain to borrow massively from the USA to finance the war — reversing the financial relationship (Britain had been the world's creditor). After WWI, Britain owed the USA, its reserves were depleted, and New York replaced London as the world financial centre","USA did not participate in WWI"], ans:2, exp:"WWI's financial transformation was decisive: Pre-war Britain held $4 billion in overseas investments; post-war it was a net debtor. The USA held $13 billion in war loans to Britain and France. Mechanically: Britain sold overseas assets to pay for war; USA lent money. The result: New York replaced London as financial capital; the dollar increasingly competed with sterling as reserve currency. This shift took full effect after WWII when Bretton Woods institutionalised dollar hegemony." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: The Depression-era agricultural crisis affected developing countries more severely than industrial countries.\nREASON: Countries dependent on primary commodity exports (grain, cotton, rubber, metals) saw prices collapse while their import costs remained relatively high.", opts:["Both A and R true; R explains the differential impact","Both true but unconnected","A true, R false","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"The terms of trade collapse was devastating for primary producers. Between 1929-33, primary commodity prices fell 60-70% while manufactured goods prices fell only 30-40%. Indian farmers who sold wheat at half price but still needed to buy ploughs at similar prices faced ruin. Argentine cattle ranchers, Ghanaian cocoa farmers, Malaysian rubber tappers — all saw their incomes collapse. This revealed the structural vulnerability of commodity-dependent economies that development economists would later theorise." },
  { q:"EXTRACT-BASED: 'Globalisation creates winners and losers — and the losers are not always in poor countries.' What evidence from the chapter supports this?", opts:["Globalisation only creates winners","Only poor countries lose from globalisation","True — Eastern European grain farmers lost when American grain flooded markets; British handloom weavers lost when power looms industrialised; German industrialists lost initially to British competition; American workers today lose manufacturing jobs to China — the 'losers' exist across the income spectrum","Globalisation is always net positive"], ans:2, exp:"This is a crucial nuance. The chapter shows multiple examples: Eastern European landlords lost when US/Argentine grain entered European markets (1870s-80s). Indian handloom weavers lost to British mills. Lancashire mill workers lost to cheaper Indian mills in the early 20th century. Globalisation creates sectoral winners and losers within countries, regardless of the country's overall development level. This is why globalisation is politically contested in both rich and poor countries — it redistributes income within as well as between nations." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: A student argues that the Bretton Woods institutions (IMF, World Bank) have been more harmful than helpful to developing countries. What is the strongest evidence for and against this claim?", opts:["Only helpful — all countries benefited","Only harmful — IMF destroyed all economies","For: IMF 'structural adjustment' conditions (cutting public spending, privatisation, deregulation) have often worsened poverty; World Bank projects have sometimes displaced communities; conditionalities reflect Western ideological preferences. Against: Bretton Woods provided 25 years of stable growth; IMF emergency lending prevented bankruptcies; World Bank financed essential infrastructure. The evidence is mixed.","No evidence exists either way"], ans:2, exp:"This is genuinely contested. The 1945-70 Bretton Woods era was economically successful globally. But from 1980s, IMF 'structural adjustment' programmes in Latin America, Africa and Asia imposed austerity, privatisation and deregulation that worsened inequality and debt in many cases. The 'Washington Consensus' proved more doctrinaire than effective. The honest assessment: these institutions provided real benefits (stability, emergency lending) while also serving Western interests and imposing damaging conditions. Complex institutions with complex legacies." },
  { q:"ASSERTION: The colonial economic system created by Britain in the 19th century is the root cause of contemporary developing-world poverty.\nREASON: Colonialism forced specialisation in raw material export, prevented industrial development, extracted wealth, and created dependent economic structures that persist today.", opts:["Both A and R true; R correctly explains the causal chain","Both true but unconnected","A overstates; R correctly describes colonial policies","A false, R true"], ans:0, exp:"This is the core of dependency theory (Frank, Wallerstein) and is substantially supported by evidence. Colonial policies: forced India to pay 'home charges' to Britain; drained Indian gold during the Depression; prevented Indian industrial development through tariff policy; created mono-crop economies in Africa; extracted mineral wealth. The structures — raw material export, import of manufactures — were built under colonialism and persist. However, some former colonies (South Korea, Taiwan, Singapore) escaped this trap through state-led industrialisation, suggesting colonial legacy is not deterministic." },
  { q:"How does the history of the 19th-century global economy challenge the claim that free markets naturally produce development?", opts:["19th century history supports free market development theory","Free markets did produce universal development","Historical evidence shows: countries that industrialised successfully (USA, Germany, Japan) used protectionist tariffs, not free trade; colonies forced into free trade remained primary commodity exporters; the Depression showed unregulated markets produce catastrophe — challenging naive free-market development theory","Markets always work if left alone"], ans:1, exp:"This is the key historical lesson of the chapter. The 19th century's most successful industrialisations — USA, Germany, Japan — were built with heavy state intervention and tariff protection. Britain's 'free trade' empire extracted wealth from colonies. The Depression showed unregulated financial markets are catastrophically unstable. Historical development economics therefore suggests that free markets are tools, not solutions — they need institutions, regulation and strategic policy to produce development rather than inequality and instability." },
  { q:"CASE-BASED: 'The potato fundamentally changed European demography and politics.' Is this claim justifiable?", opts:["Potatoes had no demographic effect","The potato only affected Ireland","Justifiable — the potato's high caloric density per acre supported population growth across Europe from the 18th century; reduced famine deaths; but also created dangerous food monoculture (Ireland). When potato blight hit (1845-49), Ireland lost 25% of its population. This shows how crop globalisation creates both opportunity and vulnerability — and how a colonial policy response (British indifference to Irish famine) has lasting political consequences (Irish independence movement)", "Potatoes only mattered economically"], ans:2, exp:"The potato's demographic impact was enormous: historians estimate it enabled 20%+ additional European population by 1800. But the Irish case shows the danger: when Ireland's potato monoculture was destroyed by blight, 1 million died and 2 million emigrated. British policy that continued exporting Irish grain during the famine while people starved radicalised Irish nationalism. The famine is a founding trauma of Irish national identity — with political consequences lasting to today." },
];


